<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="337" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,150,501]" pageId="5" pageNumber="337">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,150,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="337">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species was originally described from 
<collectingCountry box="[819,953,150,176]" name="Switzerland" pageId="5" pageNumber="337">Switzerland</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Greuter, A." box="[998,1170,150,176]" pageId="5" pageNumber="337" pagination="35 - 76" refId="ref11901" refString="Greuter, A. (1917) Beitrage zur Systematik der Gastrotrichen in der Schweiz. Revue Suisse de Zoologie, 25, 35 - 76. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. part. 31929" type="journal article" year="1917">Greuter (1917)</bibRefCitation>
; since then, it has been found twice, by 
<bibRefCitation author="Visvesvara, G." box="[334,539,186,213]" pageId="5" pageNumber="337" pagination="209 - 216" refId="ref14243" refString="Visvesvara, G. (1964) On some Gastrotricha of genus Chaetonotus from India. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 7, 209 - 216. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222936408651460" type="journal article" year="1964">Visvesvara (1964)</bibRefCitation>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[575,633,186,212]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="337">India</collectingCountry>
and by 
<bibRefCitation author="Balsamo, M." box="[724,897,186,212]" pageId="5" pageNumber="337" pagination="287 - 295" refId="ref11474" refString="Balsamo, M. (1982) Three new gastrotrichs from a Tuscan-Emilian Apennine Lake. Bollettino di Zoologia, 49, 287 - 295. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 11250008209439402" type="journal article" year="1982">Balsamo (1982</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Balsamo, M." box="[909,966,186,212]" pageId="5" pageNumber="337" pagination="1 - 92" refId="ref11510" refString="Balsamo, M. (1983) Gastrotrichi. Consiglio Nazionale delle Ricerche, Guide per il riconoscimento delle specie animali delle acque interne italiane, 20, 1 - 92." type="journal article" year="1983">1983</bibRefCitation>
) in 
<collectingCountry box="[1011,1064,186,212]" name="Italy" pageId="5" pageNumber="337">Italy</collectingCountry>
. A key character of the species is the presence of 9 ‘giant’ single barbed spines (64-84 μm in length) originating at mid-posterior trunk and arranged in three rows and three columns. Morphology of the Indian specimens agree well with the original description, except for the size; in fact, the Indian specimens appear much smaller compared to the Swiss animals (111-115 μm vs 193 μm in total length). Size of the Indian specimens approaches that of the Italian gastrotrichs, which have a total length of 106-138 μm. On the other hand, the ‘giant’ spines of the Italian specimens are double barbed. Future investiga- tions, at morphological and molecular levels, should clarify if the differences accounted fall within the intraspecific variability of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Greuter" authorityYear="1917" box="[345,501,439,465]" family="Chaetonotidae" genus="Chaetonotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chaetonotida" pageId="5" pageNumber="337" phylum="Gastrotricha" rank="species" species="novenarius">
<emphasis box="[345,501,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="337">C. novenarius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxon or are instead clues of populations distinctness i.e., specimens from the three countries belong to three distinct species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
